<protolog id="rid.8397_nm.13057" type="description" xmlns="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://namesforlife.com/ns/protolog file:/C:/NamesforLife/workspace/namesforlife-schema/protolog.xsd"><organism doi="10.1601/nm.13057" rank="genus">Alkanibacter</organism><reference id="rid.8397"><citation citation-type="journal"><authors><person-name><surname>Friedrich</surname><given-names>M.M.</given-names></person-name><person-name><surname>Lipski</surname><given-names>A.</given-names></person-name></authors><article-title>Alkanibacter difficilis gen. nov., sp. nov. and Singularimonas variicoloris gen. nov., sp. nov., hexane-degrading bacteria isolated from a hexane-treated biofilter.</article-title><year>2008</year><volume>58</volume><issue>10</issue><fpage>2324</fpage><lpage>2329</lpage><source id="117">International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology</source><abbrev>Int J Syst Evol Microbiol</abbrev><issn>1466-5026</issn><essn>1466-5034</essn><pub-id pub-id-type="doi">10.1099/ijs.0.65517-0</pub-id><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">18842850</pub-id></citation></reference><content><p class="title"><s>Description of <em>Alkanibacter</em> gen. nov.</s></p><p class="etymology"><s><em>Alkanibacter</em> (Al.ka.ni.bac′ter. N.L. n. <em>alkanum</em> saturated hydrocarbon; N.L. masc. n. <em>bacter</em> from Gr. n. <em>bakterion</em> rod; N.L. masc. n. <em>Alkanibacter</em> rod assimilating alkanes).</s></p><p class="description"><s>Cells are aerobic, non-spore-forming rods.</s><s>Gram-negative and oxidase- and catalase-positive.</s><s>The major fatty acids are 16 : 0 and 18 : 1<em>cis</em>11.</s><s>The quinone type is ubiquinone-8.</s><s>The type species is <em>Alkanibacter difficilis</em>.</s></p></content></protolog>